Solid priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared from the aftermath of COVID-19.
However, the world's most "fragile" states are facing a particularly complex set of problems.
In fact, before the pandemic began, Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and other countries were already grappling with poverty, conflict, corruption, and a dysfunctional public administration.
Today, these factors leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What each country needs to get through the pandemic is precisely what fragile states lack: a functioning state apparatus able to develop and implement an action plan, an effective police force to enforce the rules, social programs that provide funds, supplies, and health services to treat infected individuals.
The state's lack of resources is immediately felt in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
Mali has only three ventilators for the entire country.
An effective response also relies on trust in the state's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states hardly enjoys the consent of the population.
In countries recovering from conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, several people will be hesitant to support the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect taxes to help those who cannot.
However, in fragile states, the official economy is not present enough to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would evade the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to their demographic weight of young people and geographical distance.
However, from our perspective as co-presidents of the new Council on State Fragility, it is clear that this was not the case.
In recent weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all had infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries that were first hit by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more significant for fragile states. These will not only be the result of national lockdowns, but also of what happens abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from expatriates have fallen, prices of basic goods and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for most of their food, we are increasingly talking about "hunger" and even "famine".
We should now understand that the problems of less wealthy countries have become mostly global problems, whether in the form of massive migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the disadvantaged populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will only worsen.
That's why the Council on State Fragility has made it an absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges that these countries must face.
The council, composed of former world leaders, ministers, diplomats, business leaders, academics, and development organization presidents, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its goal will be to guide national and international policymakers on how fragile states will navigate this crisis and address their broader and deeper problems.
Decentralization, adaptability, and data-driven decision-making will be essential.
For example, it is widely proven that targeted "lockdowns" of local outbreaks are often more appropriate than national lockdowns.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
However, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades away.
We propose five recommendations.
Firstly, access to social protection must be simpler and faster.
At times, this will mean universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile phone networks should be leveraged to collect information on immediate needs and disburse small regular payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which cultivated rice, has become increasingly dependent on it over the past few decades.
More broadly, Africa accounts for 60% of the world's unused arable land.
Local production initiatives for staple crops must be rapidly scaled up to a much larger extent.
Thirdly, as soon as vaccine production is launched, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by wealthier countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As noted by the most involved financial institutions in international development; small businesses in less affluent countries are often neglected and suffer from the negative consequences of broader objectives and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
However, it is precisely these small businesses that need greater investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support highly indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid will repay around $40 billion to private and public creditors this year alone.
To prevent this financial shock, we urge all G20 members to suspend accumulated debts not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Furthermore, it is essential that all fragile states receive emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions — particularly countries that do not typically have access to World Bank or International Monetary Fund financing.
The COVID-19 pandemic will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we can mitigate the worst impacts of the pandemic.
If there is one lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that lives and livelihoods will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
